1
00:00:03,840 --> 00:00:08,150
[Tom] Eight minutes past ten. Gary Stevenson is
an economist who focuses on inequality,

2
00:00:08,160 --> 00:00:13,190
a former trader who retired from the
City as a multi-millionaire,

3
00:00:13,200 --> 00:00:18,870
aged 27, after correctly predicting that
the 2008 financial crash

4
00:00:18,880 --> 00:00:22,470
would happen. Mr Stevenson, thank you for
joining the programme tonight.

5
00:00:22,480 --> 00:00:24,710
[Gary] Thanks for having me, Tom.

6
00:00:24,720 --> 00:00:27,109
[Tom] Who's going to pay for all of this?

7
00:00:27,119 --> 00:00:30,950
[Gary] Well, you said a very interesting thing
in your introduction, which was that

8
00:00:30,960 --> 00:00:34,389
we're breaking all the rules this time,
and I think that really

9
00:00:34,399 --> 00:00:38,709
sums up quite well, because what is
happening right now with

10
00:00:38,719 --> 00:00:43,430
government borrowing is very, very
different from what normally happens
with government borrowing.

11
00:00:43,440 --> 00:00:48,549
Now normally, when the government needs
money, it goes out and borrows from wealthy
investors,

12
00:00:48,559 --> 00:00:53,350
pension funds, maybe foreign governments.
This time, that's not happening.

13
00:00:53,360 --> 00:00:57,990
All the money that the government has
borrowed to deal with the COVID crisis
so far

14
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:02,709
has been borrowed from the Bank of
England. And the Bank of England, as you
know,

15
00:01:02,719 --> 00:01:06,789
is essentially a government institution,
an independent one,

16
00:01:06,799 --> 00:01:13,030
but it is one. The Bank of England has
got this money by printing it.

17
00:01:13,040 --> 00:01:16,149
And that's what's taking a bit of time to
think about here.

18
00:01:16,159 --> 00:01:22,630
You know, this is literally quantitative
easing, right? We're just
printing the cash to keep the cash coming.

19
00:01:22,640 --> 00:01:26,230
[Tom] Yeah, exactly. The Bank of England...
but the Bank of England is printing money,

20
00:01:26,240 --> 00:01:31,030
just like it did after 2008, but this
time the amount of money the Bank of
England is printing

21
00:01:31,040 --> 00:01:35,270
is pretty much exactly the same as the
amount of money the government is
spending.

22
00:01:35,280 --> 00:01:38,310
Which means essentially all of this
money is coming from

23
00:01:38,320 --> 00:01:41,910
government printing. Now, that puts us in
a very interesting situation.

24
00:01:41,920 --> 00:01:46,950
[Gary] It is, as you say, breaking all the rules.
When you start funding with printed
money,

25
00:01:46,960 --> 00:01:50,069
it really raises the question:
do you pay it back?

26
00:01:50,079 --> 00:01:54,069
[Tom] Yep.

[Gary] Because the government here is...
it's printing the money.

27
00:01:54,079 --> 00:01:57,429
It's borrowing it from the Bank of
England, but the Bank of England is
printing it.

28
00:01:57,439 --> 00:02:01,590
And in the past, whenever we've seen
governments do this, the money does not
get paid back.

29
00:02:01,600 --> 00:02:08,389
And interestingly, the money does not
have to be paid back, because the money
is being borrowed from another branch of
government.

30
00:02:08,399 --> 00:02:12,710
You don't have to pay any interest on it,
and in all the time this has been done
in the past,

31
00:02:12,720 --> 00:02:18,390
we've been doing it for more than ten
years now, many countries have.
When it has come to maturity, the central

32
00:02:18,400 --> 00:02:22,470
bank has said, "Okay, have another ten
years," and they've continued to allow
it to be extended. So, you know,

33
00:02:23,680 --> 00:02:27,750
really, what is a debt if you don't have
to pay any interest and you never have
to pay it back?

34
00:02:27,760 --> 00:02:35,040
[Tom] So, yes, it depends, I guess, what
proportion of the amount that we are
borrowing, at nearly a billion quid a
day,

35
00:02:35,360 --> 00:02:39,030
is being done through the printing of
money by the Bank of England. Because

36
00:02:39,040 --> 00:02:44,229
the country does borrow, and it's a
question that a lot of people, I think,
ask perfectly legitimately when we talk
about government borrowing.

37
00:02:46,239 --> 00:02:51,110
Who are they going to borrow the
money from? Who do they ring up to say,
"Okay, can you put the money in my account

38
00:02:51,120 --> 00:02:55,430
by Thursday?" You know, the £258 billion
that are being borrowed.

39
00:02:55,440 --> 00:03:00,710
And it's normally, as you say, pension
funds and other nations.

40
00:03:00,720 --> 00:03:04,390
But this time you say that's not
happening, it's coming from a different
source. And the source...

41
00:03:04,400 --> 00:03:08,869
[Gary] Yeah, this time it's... yeah, it really
matches really well. The amount of
money the government's borrowing

42
00:03:08,879 --> 00:03:13,430
in this crisis, the amount of money it's
spending, its deficit spending, to help
deal with COVID,

43
00:03:13,440 --> 00:03:17,509
is almost exactly the same as the amount
of money that the central bank is
printing, which in this case I think is

44
00:03:17,519 --> 00:03:23,990
£300 billion. An enormous amount of money.
I think that works out something like
£5,000 per person in the country.

45
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:29,750
Huge amount of money. So it's being
printed by the central bank, which is
essentially part of the government.

46
00:03:29,760 --> 00:03:34,949
What that means is it will not be paid
back. Yeah, I used to work in financial
markets, I still talk to people in

47
00:03:34,959 --> 00:03:39,750
financial markets. Everyone in financial
markets knows that money is not being
paid back.

48
00:03:39,760 --> 00:03:43,910
Really, which raises the question: why
don't governments do this all the time?

49
00:03:43,920 --> 00:03:47,430
[Tom] So, hang on a second. So, Gary,
you're saying that the people that
you're speaking to,

50
00:03:47,440 --> 00:03:52,789
the... you're now presumably retired from
at the age of 30 — my God, I need to
ask you about that in a minute —

51
00:03:52,799 --> 00:03:57,910
but that all the finance guys down in
the City, they're all saying to

52
00:03:57,920 --> 00:04:00,229
you, "Gary, this is never going to be
paid off." This is just not going to
happen?

53
00:04:00,239 --> 00:04:04,149
[Gary] Yeah. They stopped looking at
government debt. What they look at now is
government debt

54
00:04:04,159 --> 00:04:10,309
minus the amount borrowed from the
central bank, because nobody ever expects
that to be paid back.

55
00:04:10,319 --> 00:04:13,990
Which raises the question: what is going
to happen?

[Tom] Yeah, what are the consequences of it?

56
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:18,390
[Gary] Yeah, quite. And I think really the
interesting question is what does that
mean, because,

57
00:04:18,400 --> 00:04:24,629
like you say, we're breaking all the
rules here. We're doing huge amounts of
deficit spending funded by printed money,

58
00:04:24,639 --> 00:04:30,950
and we really need to ask... I mean, the
question which people are asking, "How do
you pay it back?" — that's the wrong
question.

59
00:04:30,960 --> 00:04:37,670
The question is: what are the
consequences of printing such huge
amounts of money to fund a government
deficit? That is the question we need to
ask.

60
00:04:37,680 --> 00:04:42,390
[Tom] And what would be your answer?

61
00:04:42,400 --> 00:04:48,950
[Gary] Well, you need to look at what happens to
the money. You know, the reason
governments don't normally do this is
because it leads to a huge increase in
the money supply,

62
00:04:48,960 --> 00:04:53,909
and that has an effect on the economy. So
in this crisis, what's happened is, you
know, a lot of

63
00:04:53,919 --> 00:04:57,909
ordinary people have lost their income,
they've lost their jobs and they're
losing money. But if you

64
00:04:57,919 --> 00:05:03,189
look at richer people, those people have
often kept their incomes, and their
spending has collapsed.

65
00:05:03,199 --> 00:05:07,510
So if you actually look at the amount of
money being saved by higher-income
people and richer people,

66
00:05:07,520 --> 00:05:13,909
it's gone through the roof. So richer
people are accumulating a lot of money in
their bank accounts as a result of this
policy.

67
00:05:13,919 --> 00:05:18,310
So when we talk about going back to
normal after COVID, we're not going to be
going back to normal. No, we're going to

68
00:05:18,320 --> 00:05:22,790
be going back to a normal where the
richest people in the country have
massive bank accounts

69
00:05:22,800 --> 00:05:28,150
full of a lot of cash.

[Tom] And, Gary, to ask, what does that do?
And, Gary, the

70
00:05:28,160 --> 00:05:35,590
difference too, which I'm sort of still
trying to get my head around again, being
an absolute dunce on this stuff,

71
00:05:35,600 --> 00:05:39,590
the difference between what you see in
the stock market — and the stock market
prices did...

72
00:05:39,600 --> 00:05:45,830
I mean, in America, the stock market
there, it's like nothing happened, I mean
it's just carrying on

73
00:05:45,840 --> 00:05:51,670
normal. House prices — you look at house
prices, we're expecting... someone was
saying the banks were predicting an 18%

74
00:05:51,680 --> 00:05:55,350
drop in house prices — they're carrying
on, just chugging along, ticking over.

75
00:05:55,360 --> 00:06:02,070
That the asset economy seems to be
carrying on as normal. The real economy —
bricks and mortar shops on the high
street, people's jobs —

76
00:06:03,199 --> 00:06:06,309
is falling apart. Why is that?

77
00:06:06,319 --> 00:06:10,550
[Gary] Yeah, oh, that is exactly right, and it's
exactly because of what we just said
here. The government has printed huge
amounts of money,

78
00:06:10,560 --> 00:06:14,550
and that has ended up in the bank
accounts of wealthier people.

79
00:06:14,560 --> 00:06:19,430
Now, you know, I come from an ordinary
background, but I work with a lot of
wealthy people from the UK, from the US.

80
00:06:19,440 --> 00:06:22,550
If you give wealthy people a lot of
money, they're going to invest it.

81
00:06:22,560 --> 00:06:26,469
Yeah, and in the US, they're often in
stocks and shares. In this country,

82
00:06:26,479 --> 00:06:31,670
that means... yeah, you can go back and
look at my... right at the beginning of
the crisis, a lot of people were
predicting a fall.

83
00:06:31,680 --> 00:06:36,710
I was predicting a rise, and I was buying
everything, because if you give rich
people a load of money,

84
00:06:36,720 --> 00:06:41,590
they will buy things. If you look at
2008, everybody thought prices would
crash, but in the end,

85
00:06:41,600 --> 00:06:46,150
London house prices doubled, and that was
because of huge amounts of money
printing going to richer people.

86
00:06:46,160 --> 00:06:50,629
That will happen again here. That is the
real cost.

87
00:06:50,639 --> 00:06:54,390
[Tom] Let me talk about who's going to pay for
the crisis. What happens if London house
prices double again? What happens though,
Gary?

88
00:06:54,400 --> 00:06:59,990
[Gary] It's so interesting. The house price
thing is really interesting. What happens
if there is an inflationary shock? If

89
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:05,189
inflation is at 0.5%, it's gone up but
it's still only at 0.5%. If you just
print money,

90
00:07:05,199 --> 00:07:12,070
you get to some examples like, you know,
everyone knows the pictures of the
wheelbarrows of cash being run around
Europe in the 1930s.

91
00:07:12,080 --> 00:07:15,189
[Tom] So if there's an inflationary shock,
we're screwed?

92
00:07:15,199 --> 00:07:19,189
[Gary] With this amount of cash flying around,
whether you're screwed or not depends on
who you are.

93
00:07:19,199 --> 00:07:23,909
If you're one of the people who's sitting
with a bank account full of cash now,
which a lot of the richer people in this
country are,

94
00:07:23,919 --> 00:07:27,749
then that's just fine for you. My worry
is what happens to the ordinary people

95
00:07:27,759 --> 00:07:31,990
when prices go up. What happens to
ordinary people if house prices double?
You know, it's hard enough for

96
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:37,110
some ordinary families to get houses in
this city, right? If they double again,
you're telling, like,

97
00:07:37,120 --> 00:07:41,189
two-thirds of the kids, "You're never
going to get one." So really,
if you're talking about how do we deal

98
00:07:41,199 --> 00:07:45,670
with this crisis, who's going to pay it
back, it's going to be the poorer kids,
because the richer

99
00:07:45,680 --> 00:07:51,430
guys, those guys are loaded, they're
making a fortune on this.

100
00:07:51,440 --> 00:07:55,589
So really, it's a problem of inequality
and distribution. That is the problem.

101
00:07:55,599 --> 00:08:01,189
So actually, the way in which you pay
this back... as you say, it's the wrong
question that's being asked, because it's
not the...

102
00:08:01,199 --> 00:08:05,990
the debt that we're borrowing to fund
the COVID response, we're never going to
pay that back.

103
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:10,950
That's fine, we'll write that off. What
needs to happen is the payback to

104
00:08:10,960 --> 00:08:16,469
deal with the inequality that is about
to come. Because, as you say, all the
rich people sit there getting richer,
buying their houses,

105
00:08:16,479 --> 00:08:22,869
you know, trading off property — property
guys — and the poorer people whose
real economy has been decimated by this,

106
00:08:22,879 --> 00:08:26,309
they're left with nothing because they
don't have any assets.

107
00:08:26,319 --> 00:08:30,869
[Tom] Exactly.

[Gary] Exactly. That is a big question. The
media is asking, "How do you pay the debt
back?"

108
00:08:30,879 --> 00:08:36,709
That's the wrong question. Everybody in
finance knows the debt doesn't get paid
back. The real question is: what's going
to happen to the money?

109
00:08:36,719 --> 00:08:42,469
That's going to rich people. It's going
to push asset prices up. It is going to
cause a crisis in home affordability and
inequality.

110
00:08:42,479 --> 00:08:51,110
So really, the problem we're going to
have coming out of this is: how do we
deal with that massive rising inequality
and the impossibility of getting housing
for ordinary people?

111
00:08:51,120 --> 00:08:56,070
[Tom] And just a word on, because I'm getting
lots of people texting and saying,
"Inflation, inflation, inflation."

112
00:08:56,080 --> 00:08:59,350
How do you keep inflation low enough so
that you don't

113
00:08:59,360 --> 00:09:02,310
have wheelbarrows full of cash being
wheeled around?

114
00:09:02,320 --> 00:09:04,550
[Gary] There's two different kinds of
inflation, which is inflation out on the
streets

115
00:09:04,560 --> 00:09:09,430
and inflation in asset prices. After 2008,
we didn't see much inflation in shops.

116
00:09:09,440 --> 00:09:12,550
We didn't see... but we saw a huge amount
of inflation eventually in assets. So the

117
00:09:12,560 --> 00:09:15,030
thing that's happening here is loads and
loads of people are losing their jobs,

118
00:09:15,519 --> 00:09:20,630
and when people lose their jobs, that
makes the job market really, really weak,
and people don't get pay rises.

119
00:09:20,640 --> 00:09:25,509
As long as pay rises aren't happening,
then you don't get much inflation.
So that's the reason why after 2008 we

120
00:09:25,519 --> 00:09:30,870
didn't see inflation. Now, I'm not saying
necessarily that's going to happen again.
The amount of money being printed here,

121
00:09:30,880 --> 00:09:37,030
it's... well, it's much quicker,
definitely, than it was in 2008. There is
a risk that we lose control of it and
inflation does increase,

122
00:09:37,040 --> 00:09:43,509
especially once COVID passes and, like
we've said, all of these people with huge
amounts of cash in their bank start
trying to spend it. That is definitely a
possibility.

123
00:09:45,279 --> 00:09:49,670
I think, if you remember, after 2008,
2010, 2011, we did have quite high
inflation, five percent...

124
00:09:49,680 --> 00:09:53,110
[Tom] Yeah, coming up to six percent.

[Gary] That's right. And then

125
00:09:53,120 --> 00:09:59,350
the Bank of England, rather sensibly I
suspect, decided to leave the money out
there, not take any money back.

126
00:09:59,360 --> 00:10:04,310
Leave the easy money. The Bank of England,
if it happens, you know, if it's five,
six percent, which,

127
00:10:04,320 --> 00:10:08,310
you know, I don't want to make any exact
predictions, but it could be at some
point coming out of this,

128
00:10:08,320 --> 00:10:16,389
I think the bank will allow it to
continue, but what that will cause is a
cost-of-living crisis for ordinary
people, just like it did after 2008.

129
00:10:16,399 --> 00:10:21,509
[Tom] Gary, you've been fascinating talking to
you. I'm already incredibly late for the

130
00:10:21,519 --> 00:10:28,790
bits I need to hit on the programme.
I've got to ask you, what's it like to
be 27 with multiple millions in the bank
account?

131
00:10:28,800 --> 00:10:36,310
[Gary] Well, it's unusual. Like I said, I
didn't grow up with money,

132
00:10:36,320 --> 00:10:40,470
and I made the money very quickly, and it
all came very quickly to me.

133
00:10:40,480 --> 00:10:42,710
[Tom] Okay, well, let me ask you this, it's
very funny, you're gonna have to be
really brief, Gary. I am

134
00:10:42,720 --> 00:10:49,350
obsessed with this idea, right? So there
you are, it doesn't matter what age you
are, who you are,

135
00:10:49,360 --> 00:10:55,670
there is a moment in your life where you
suddenly realise you've got more money
than you ever possibly could have dreamt
of,

136
00:10:55,680 --> 00:11:03,829
that it's there for you, and your whole
world has just shifted on its axis
because you've got this money in your
bank account,

137
00:11:03,839 --> 00:11:07,110
and it's for you. When was that moment
for you?

138
00:11:07,120 --> 00:11:11,829
[Gary] For me, when was that? Well, that was
when I got my first bonus and I realised I
should have spent my whole childhood

139
00:11:11,839 --> 00:11:17,030
buying Boots meal deals. Yeah, that was
it. But before I go, I'd just like to
suggest that if anyone

140
00:11:17,040 --> 00:11:22,550
wants to know more about the effects of
money printing, there is a really good
video on my YouTube, Gary's Economics,

141
00:11:22,560 --> 00:11:24,150
explaining exactly how it works.

142
00:11:24,160 --> 00:11:29,990
[Tom] Great, man. Gary Stevenson, thank you for
your time. An economist focusing on
inequality, former trader, retired from
the City. Multi-millionaire, aged 27.

